~=~=~=~=~
|| MBF ||
~=~=~=~=~
   mbf is a modified implementation of the esoteric programming language Brainfuck (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brainfuck), with the addition of macros along with it.

`mbf` stands for "macro brainfuck".

~=~=~=~=~=~=~=~=~
|| HELLO WORLD ||
~=~=~=~=~=~=~=~=~
   ###################
   # hello_world.mbf #
   ###################

   # hello macro
   hello {
      > 8+ [< 9+ > -] < .
      > 4+ [< 7+ > -] > +.
      7+ . .
      3+ .
      >> 6+ [< 7+ >-] < ++.
      12- .
      > 6+ [< 9+ >-] < + .
      <.
      3+ .
      6- .
      8- .
      >>> 4+ [< 8+ >-] <+ .
   }

   # call hello
   hello;

   #########
   # SHELL #
   #########
   
   % # use `mbf -h` for help
   
   % mbf ./hello_world.mbf
   Hello, World!

   % mbf -E expanded.bf hello_world.mbf
   [SUCCESS] file was successfully written!
   
   % cat expanded.bf
   >++++++++[<+++++++++>-]<.>++++[<+++++++>-]<+.+++++++..+++.>>++++++[<+++++++>-]<++.------------.>++++++[<+++++++++>-]<+.<.+++.------.--------.>>>++++[<++++++++>-]<+.

~=~=~=~=~=~=~=
|| FEATURES ||
~=~=~=~=~=~=~=
o   Strict superset of BF
o   100% compatible with ordinary BF
o   Includes an interpreter to execute MBF/BF code
o   Lets you know when you make a syntax error
o   Supports comments
o   Macros can call another macros
o   Insensitive to whitespaces/indentation
o   Lets you save the compiled BF code
o   Includes =-h= / =--help= option for help

~=~=~=~=~=~=~=~=
|| HOW TO USE ||
~=~=~=~=~=~=~=~=
o   Prerequisites:
       o   GNU Make
       o   C compiler

o   Clone this repository into =mbf/= and =cd= into it:
       % git clone https://github.com/vs-123/mbf.git
       % ls
       ./ ../ mbf/
       % cd mbf/

o   Ensure you set =CC= environment variable in case =make= fails to find your C compiler.

o   Use =make= to build the project:
       % pwd
       ~/mbf
       
       % make build
       [INFO] building...
       [SUCCESS] successfully built!
       
       % ls build/ && cd $_
       ./ ../ mbf*
       
       % ./mbf ../examples/hello_world.mbf
       Hello, World!

o   To run tests, use =make test=:
       % make test
       [INFO] building tests...
       [INFO] running tests...
      
o   To perform a clean operation, use =make clean=:
       % make clean
       [INFO] cleaning...
       [SUCCESS] cleaned successfully!

~=~=~=~=~=~=~=
